00:24:44.878 --> 00:24:59.578
Incoming livestream: It's a double-edged sword, because if the agent decided this is not reachable, I would have never seen it, probably. Anyway, so this is the current design. We've got a set of scripts doing all the deterministic bits and bobs, and we've got a bug hunter looking for bugs.


124
00:24:59.578 --> 00:25:08.317
Incoming livestream: We've got, bug deduplicator deduplicating the bugs, we've got the obfuscator cleaning up the code, we've got another agent who


125
00:25:08.318 --> 00:25:17.968
Incoming livestream: like, reformat the reports to JSON, and we've got a bug verifier. And then we've got, obviously, on the MCP side, JAX and SuitUp.


126
00:25:18.358 --> 00:25:29.608
Incoming livestream: Roadmap, maybe some sort of static analysis integration, start running static analyzers and let the agent triage the bugs coming out of the static analyzer.


127
00:25:29.608 --> 00:25:52.208
Incoming livestream: Maybe some sort of way to start tracking bugs across different apps, because at the minute, the agent can only see bugs within one app, and, like, there's no… like, very often you need to start chaining things together across multiple apps in order to get a useful primitive out of them, and a useful exploit. So maybe some sort of database where the agent can see all of the bugs we've got at the minute.


128
00:25:52.428 --> 00:26:14.498
Incoming livestream: And last but not least, and actually something we've been working on, introduce some POC generation and runtime proof of vulnerability, so you plug your phone into your laptop, you run ADB MCP, you run Frida MCP, and you let the agent test the trigger produced by the bug report, by the bug hunter, and then refine the POC


129
00:26:14.498 --> 00:26:21.088
Incoming livestream: while collecting some events using Frida Hooks and ADB LockCat, events.


130
00:26:21.348 --> 00:26:25.058
Incoming livestream: And… that is it. Thank you.


