00:27:01.518 --> 00:27:07.507
Incoming livestream: breaking the lethal… excuse me, breaking the lethal trifecta, so please welcome Andrew.


135
00:27:34.588 --> 00:27:35.978
Incoming livestream: Hello?


136
00:27:38.898 --> 00:27:39.937
Incoming livestream: Oh, yes.


137
00:27:49.338 --> 00:27:56.117
Incoming livestream: Great. So, hey everyone, it's great to see you all. I'm Andrew, I'm the head of the AI security team at Stripe.


138
00:27:56.218 --> 00:28:10.557
Incoming livestream: And I've been at Stripe for about 10 years now, and, I mean, I guess a lot of people ask me why I'm still here. Unfortunately, I'm a nerd who loves solving problems, and I've yet to find another, way to keep my ADHD brain entertained.


139
00:28:10.728 --> 00:28:17.887
Incoming livestream: But in these 10 years, I've lived through, you know, many product launches, many reorgs,


140
00:28:18.208 --> 00:28:24.898
Incoming livestream: you know, the slow, dignified graying of Patrick's hair. And I can honestly say that this moment


141
00:28:24.898 --> 00:28:40.277
Incoming livestream: Sort of this work in security, in this age of AI is some of the most exciting work that, you know, I've, I've experienced in my entire career. And so, I am here to talk to you about the, possibly most exciting and also most terrifying…


142
00:28:40.338 --> 00:28:49.367
Incoming livestream: aspect of, being in this new AI age, which is prompt injection, and sort of the approaches that we're taking at Stripe to mitigating the risk there.


143
00:28:50.108 --> 00:29:04.128
Incoming livestream: So, we have an elephant in the room. You know, I think in this community, we spend a lot of time thinking and talking about prompt injection, but I find that most people working in AI are sort of scrupulously avoiding it.


144
00:29:04.128 --> 00:29:15.737
Incoming livestream: You know, given the AI hype cycle, all the focus on building things really, really fast, there's not a lot of consideration of risk. We're very much back in a move-fast-and-break-things era.


145
00:29:15.758 --> 00:29:31.468
Incoming livestream: And it's just easier for a lot of companies to pretend prompt injection doesn't exist and hope there won't be a problem, which ultimately means just letting the user, you know, beware the risk to them. You know, see, open claw, of course.


146
00:29:32.758 --> 00:29:52.237
Incoming livestream: And so, while I'm sure everyone here, you know, understands prompt injection quite well, I've actually been very surprised at how many other, you know, people in AI, you know, experienced AI developers, you know, startup founders, tech executives that I talk to only have a really vague understanding of what prompt injection is.


147
00:29:53.198 --> 00:30:02.497
Incoming livestream: Because ultimately, prompt induction is a really inconvenient risk. And that's why I think we as a security, you know, as security practitioners have a really important


148
00:30:02.628 --> 00:30:14.698
Incoming livestream: responsibility to show to the industry that not only is it, you know, a real risk, but it does not actually, mean that we can't move fast on AI. We need to help


149
00:30:14.838 --> 00:30:21.217
Incoming livestream: you know, all of our companies, you know, the people building AI move fast while not YOLOing security.


150
00:30:21.978 --> 00:30:31.158
Incoming livestream: So, you know, I'm sure a lot of you have, seen this graph from last year about failure rates, in resisting prompt ejection attacks.


151
00:30:31.168 --> 00:30:44.238
Incoming livestream: You know, models are getting better, but I think in security, you know, even a 1%, even a 0.1% failure chance to attack is not enough. So we need something better. We need something better than just, relying on the models.


152
00:30:44.848 --> 00:31:03.987
Incoming livestream: And also, this is not a future problem. Another elephant that is hiding behind the first elephant is that we don't really know, especially with consumers, how prevalent prompt ejection attacks are, and we don't know how prevalent that they are gonna be in the future. But I personally believe that,


153
00:31:04.518 --> 00:31:11.318
Incoming livestream: You know, once again, looking at things like Open Claw, things are gonna get a lot worse before they get better.


154
00:31:11.978 --> 00:31:18.537
Incoming livestream: So what do we do? You know, how do we protect our companies from the risks of prompt injection?


155
00:31:18.838 --> 00:31:27.778
Incoming livestream: Well, I have a confession to make. I am not here to announce a magical technical solution that allows us to solve prompt injection without any risk.


156
00:31:28.018 --> 00:31:35.077
Incoming livestream: I'm gonna tell you something that you probably already know, which is that we basically have to assume prompt injections will happen.


157
00:31:35.508 --> 00:31:39.098
Incoming livestream: And prevent compromised agents from causing harms,


158
00:31:39.258 --> 00:31:42.497
Incoming livestream: Compromised agents from causing harm when they do happen.


159
00:31:42.698 --> 00:31:53.628
Incoming livestream: But I will share with you a set of architectural controls that we have built at Stripe that serve as guardrails to prevent those bad things from happening when prompt injection does happen.


160
00:31:54.198 --> 00:31:58.687
Incoming livestream: But the guardrails are really only a small part of the story.


161
00:31:59.008 --> 00:32:07.227
Incoming livestream: what happens when you put these guardrails in place is that there are negative impacts on, sort of, what agents can do. There's friction for users.


162
00:32:07.398 --> 00:32:24.917
Incoming livestream: addressing those problems is really what takes, sort of a technical solution into a workable solution for your business. And, you know, that's sort of the real work, I think, in many cases, of security practitioners.


163
00:32:25.418 --> 00:32:42.197
Incoming livestream: This is sort of, ultimately, a security leadership talk. You know, when practicing security engineering, you know, step one is the threat model, step two is the mitigation, but importantly, step three is figuring out how to put in place the mitigation in a way that the business still can achieve its goal.


164
00:32:42.608 --> 00:32:57.157
Incoming livestream: And so with prompt injection, the interesting part is what happens, after we put in place the guardrails? How do we enforce it? And, you know, what do we do to make it so that agents can still be powerful?


165
00:32:57.458 --> 00:33:08.918
Incoming livestream: And so I'm gonna, tell you a little bit about how we've tried to navigate this sort of frothy, FOMO-driven world, while still remaining secure.


166
00:33:10.448 --> 00:33:30.048
Incoming livestream: Cool. So, what are the controls? Okay. Well, first let's start with data exfiltration, one of the two bad things that can happen when you get prompt injected. I'm sure you're all familiar with the lethal trifecta, you know, this term coined by Simon Willison. You know, there are three things that a agent needs in order to,


167
00:33:30.377 --> 00:33:37.638
Incoming livestream: exfiltrate data if it gets prompt-injected. One is untrusted content.


168
00:33:37.878 --> 00:33:43.508
Incoming livestream: Untrusted content is really not feasible in most cases, I think, for us to,


169
00:33:43.668 --> 00:33:48.528
Incoming livestream: you know, remove as a guardrail. You know, first of all.


170
00:33:48.658 --> 00:33:55.597
Incoming livestream: A big part of why LLMs are useful in the first place is you can just throw a bunch of stuff at them, and they will figure out what to do.


171
00:33:55.818 --> 00:34:07.478
Incoming livestream: And beyond that, you know, attackers have been very, very creative in figuring out, ways to sneak prompt injections into places you wouldn't think to look for untrusted content.


172
00:34:07.738 --> 00:34:16.228
Incoming livestream: Similarly, there's private data, and while there are totally many applications that don't need private data to work,


173
00:34:16.228 --> 00:34:33.838
Incoming livestream: there are a lot that do, and certainly at Stripe, we have a lot, you know, whether it's support tickets, emails, etc, many, many agents need private data, which means that there's really only one leg of the legal trifecta that we can focus on for mitigating prompt injection risk, which is egress.


174
00:34:33.838 --> 00:34:55.808
Incoming livestream: So, our focus has been, from a guardrail perspective, very much on preventing egress, which, one is egress to the public internet, just making general web requests. And then there's another sneaky one, which is being really careful about how you talk to third parties. You know, a very easy way to exfiltrate data would be writing it to a public Google Doc with a Google Doc tool.


175
00:34:56.328 --> 00:34:59.067
Incoming livestream: So that's guard wheel one, preventing egress.


176
00:34:59.788 --> 00:35:16.808
Incoming livestream: Second, unfortunately, there isn't a, you know, term officially for, the things that you need in order to have prompt injection, deal damage by taking a sensitive action, but I guess, lacking something better, I will call this the lethal bifecta.


177
00:35:16.858 --> 00:35:20.338
Incoming livestream: And essentially, we're in the same boat, where,


178
00:35:20.718 --> 00:35:35.778
Incoming livestream: Preventing untrusted content is not really that feasible for most agents. So instead, we focus on, preventing agents from unilaterally taking sensitive actions. Sensitive is very load-bearing here,


179
00:35:35.778 --> 00:35:48.197
Incoming livestream: Generally, the rule of thumb that I say is that anything that is a production right or extra… like a, broad communication or sending a message are the big things that we think of as sensitive actions.


180
00:35:49.408 --> 00:35:53.037
Incoming livestream: So, great, problem solved, we have our guardrails.


181
00:35:53.618 --> 00:36:10.867
Incoming livestream: Unfortunately, these guardrails cause problems. They cause agents to be less useful, and worse, they cause agents to be very annoying. I'm sure everyone here has had a very similar experience using Claude code for the first time, where,


182
00:36:10.898 --> 00:36:28.778
Incoming livestream: you know, Claude is constantly asking, can I do this, can I do this, can I do this? And it really is a bad user experience. You just start trying to, you know, find where in the settings you can enable dangerously skip permissions. So we really need to address these pain points if we want, these guardrails to be adoptable.


183
00:36:29.568 --> 00:36:33.078
Incoming livestream: So let's start with egress controls.


184
00:36:33.078 --> 00:36:56.507
Incoming livestream: You know, the common thing that I heard a lot of when I was like, hey, we need to make it so our agents can't egress to the public internet is, like, wait, you know, we need to be able to do research, we need access to public internet data. The key thing here is that what these agents generally need is not the ability to make an arbitrary HTTP request, what they need is the ability to get data from the internet. So the solution that we came to here is to offer a safe search.


185
00:36:56.638 --> 00:37:07.168
Incoming livestream: We build this on OpenAI's search, but, you know, there are other ways to do this. But the key thing here is you need to make it so that the search does not itself


186
00:37:07.168 --> 00:37:20.128
Incoming livestream: trigger egress. So there's a setting in OpenAI Web Search, external web access false, that you set so that you can make a request for a search, and it'll just serve the results to you out of the cache, and it won't,


187
00:37:20.518 --> 00:37:28.327
Incoming livestream: you know, you prevent the data from being egressed by your agent, and instead it just gets egressed by OpenAI. That's not, like…


188
00:37:28.928 --> 00:37:30.738
Incoming livestream: Really making anything any safer.


189
00:37:31.558 --> 00:37:47.527
Incoming livestream: So second is, how you, handle SaaS. So, you know, we say, hey, we have to be careful about egress, and then people are like, well, I have an MCP for my SaaS app, can't I just hook up the MCP? That's fine, right? We trust our SaaS.


190
00:37:48.238 --> 00:37:52.958
Incoming livestream: And that's sort of true, but also sort of not true.


191
00:37:53.328 --> 00:38:07.597
Incoming livestream: the way that we have approached, you know, preventing, SaaS from being a data exfiltration vector is through proxying. We have a central MCP server at Stripe called Toolshed. Basically, when we want to hook up a third-party SaaS, we will…


192
00:38:07.598 --> 00:38:14.727
Incoming livestream: proxy, basically, the connection through that central server, and then that gives us a place where we can write rules, like.


193
00:38:14.738 --> 00:38:17.748
Incoming livestream: don't allow connections to tenants that are not Stripe.


194
00:38:17.808 --> 00:38:23.297
Incoming livestream: When you're, writing data to Google Docs or Figma or whatever.


195
00:38:23.538 --> 00:38:30.728
Incoming livestream: And ultimately, this actually offers a better experience for the user, because then they only need to worry about connecting to one MCP server with their app.


196
00:38:31.658 --> 00:38:35.768
Incoming livestream: And so second, we have, the human confirmation friction.


197
00:38:35.808 --> 00:38:50.388
Incoming livestream: This is an area, I think, that there really needs to be a lot more user experience, research, but at a high level, I think of there being, like, 3 main problems, when you're doing human confirmation flow.


198
00:38:50.388 --> 00:39:06.758
Incoming livestream: One is that, like, especially in this sort of Claude Code-esque world that we are in now, the fact that the confirmation dialogue stops the agent in its tracks is a major problem. You really want to be able to start an agent doing its work and let it, you know, churn along until it's done, and then come back to it.


199
00:39:06.948 --> 00:39:21.647
Incoming livestream: Second is review fatigue, you know, see Claude code asking you to run find. And, third is rubber stamping. You know, with enough review fatigue, people are just gonna mash confirm on any confirmation dialogues.


200
00:39:22.128 --> 00:39:44.678
Incoming livestream: So, as we've been looking at the UX for this, I think that, probably the core of how we can make this a lot better for users is batching confirmations. There are a lot of, like, writes and commands that you might want to do that don't really actually need to happen instantaneously for the agent to continue making forward progress, so we can just let these stack up on the side and let the user come back to these later.


201
00:39:45.158 --> 00:40:02.088
Incoming livestream: Secondly, there are a lot of, rights where you can just do the right and then offer the user the opportunity to revert it later, and that's, like, a perfectly reasonable compromise to make sure that the agent can't, you know, do some irreversible harm.


202
00:40:02.178 --> 00:40:20.328
Incoming livestream: And then also, as we, sort of continue to get into, you know, more sophisticated policy, there are a lot of options around having an LLM as a second reviewer to make sure that people aren't rubber-stamping things to, you know, quickly tell the agent that it's trying to do something bad.


203
00:40:20.328 --> 00:40:24.007
Incoming livestream: You know, without needing to involve the human.


204
00:40:24.708 --> 00:40:36.997
Incoming livestream: So, lastly, how do we enforce this all? This is, like, very challenging when you have many, many people, writing agents in, different frameworks, across, your ecosystem.


205
00:40:37.158 --> 00:40:51.178
Incoming livestream: For egress, fortunately, we're in really good shape here at Stripe because we have a strong egress control program that predated, sort of, the world of AI agents. We have an open source repository called Smokescreen that we use for a lot of this.


206
00:40:51.178 --> 00:41:15.938
Incoming livestream: Essentially the approach here is, one, tag any service that is an AI agent. This is actually not very hard, because we know that to be an agent, you need to talk to foundation models. We have a proxy for this, but you could use, you know, whether your service talks to Bedrock or whatever as a way of doing this. And then once you have a tag on the services that are agents, you know where your egress proxy service is.


207
00:41:15.938 --> 00:41:35.558
Incoming livestream: where you know how your firewall is configured, you can just write CI checks that say, if this is an agent, you can't configure egress without some, you know, escalated review process to make sure it's following, sort of the principles of, you know, preventing data exfiltration. So that's essentially what we do at Stripe.


208
00:41:36.148 --> 00:41:40.447
Incoming livestream: So, for guardrails, things are a little bit more complicated.


209
00:41:40.708 --> 00:42:05.378
Incoming livestream: At Stripe, we have sort of two main places that people are writing tools. Either you're writing inline tools in the agent framework, or you're writing tools that are in our central MCP service. And our approach here is that we require annotations on every tool with, you know, nice human-readable properties like production impacting write, or broadcast data internally. And then based on these annotations, you can determine whether the tool needs to have some sort of human in the loop


210
00:42:05.378 --> 00:42:14.077
Incoming livestream: review. And by sort of centralizing this through a framework, you can have a central UX framework that is used for


211
00:42:14.078 --> 00:42:18.898
Incoming livestream: You know, doing those reviews and sort of improving the experience on it over time.


212
00:42:19.028 --> 00:42:33.977
Incoming livestream: Things are getting more complicated here, though, because, you know, I've heard it said by certain people that MCP is dead. Maybe not true, but increasingly, agents don't need special tools, they'll just write their own code and hit their own


213
00:42:33.978 --> 00:42:58.637
Incoming livestream: you know, hit random APIs on your existing services. So what do we do here? This is, like, work that is in progress right now, but the approach that we're looking at here is essentially proxying the connections coming out of agents, out of their sandboxes, and then using that as a choke point where you can similarly have annotations on the API endpoints that the agents are talking to, and determine which ones are sensitive, which


214
00:42:58.638 --> 00:43:03.557
Incoming livestream: Which ones need, additional, review by the, the operator?


215
00:43:04.288 --> 00:43:22.358
Incoming livestream: So yeah, to wrap up, we basically de-risk prompt injection by assuming it will happen and preventing damage. You know, two risks, data exfiltration and harmful actions. Data exfiltration, the key control is preventing egress and making sure that SaaS isn't a sneaky way to do egress.


216
00:43:22.358 --> 00:43:47.257
Incoming livestream: We solve pain points here with, safe web search and proxying of SaaS, and we use CI time controls on egress settings as our enforcement mechanism for preventing harmful actions. Human review is the key constraint. We use annotations in order to ensure things have human review, and trigger automatic human in the loop, but we need to work hard to ensure that


217
00:43:47.258 --> 00:44:04.528
Incoming livestream: the user experience of the human in-the-loop flow is good, and things like batching, reverts, you know, software and LLM-driven, checks that can happen without the human being involved, all can be applied to make this better.


218
00:44:05.348 --> 00:44:08.947
Incoming livestream: So that's it, that's what we built.


219
00:44:08.948 --> 00:44:33.877
Incoming livestream: But at some level, what I really want you to take away from this is that security isn't just about figuring out the secure way to do things, it's about helping your organization figure out how to accomplish, their goals in a secure way. And, you know, it is slightly terrifying to see all the offensive talks of ways that, you know, AI is making it easier to attack things, but it's also been really.


220
00:44:33.878 --> 00:44:46.597
Incoming livestream: exciting to see the ways in which… I think we can expect security to be much better in the near future, once we have agents really doing all of this detailed analysis of our code on an ongoing basis.


221
00:44:46.678 --> 00:45:01.568
Incoming livestream: But in order to get there, we need to make it past this sort of turbulent, high-risk era that we're in. And basically, all of us in this room are the ones that need to help our organizations do it. So, thank you.


