00:45:19.108 --> 00:45:44.037
Incoming livestream: sort of human-in-the-loop reviews. Do you find that there's any value in sort of aggregating any of that at the group or team level? Are teams, like, typically running into the same sorts of problems, or is it sort of, like, person or no review at all? I think we're probably gonna get there. We're pretty early in this. A lot of the UX experimentation is, like, very, you know, very early on. We're early on in the experimentation process.


226
00:45:44.038 --> 00:45:50.157
Incoming livestream: but I think in general, trying to find ways to,


227
00:45:50.508 --> 00:46:00.888
Incoming livestream: you know, make it so that people need to stop less, fewer checks, fewer reviews need to be made, while ensuring that human judgment is applied at the right time is going to be sort of the North Star here.


228
00:46:02.508 --> 00:46:18.958
Incoming livestream: Awesome, thank you. Quick question, do you still find the value in doing, like, threat meddling to stop, like, prompt ejections, at least partially, as you design systems? Yeah, I think that there is 100% a place for, you know, detective and,


229
00:46:18.998 --> 00:46:23.177
Incoming livestream: Sort of other types of controls that, sort of are not,


230
00:46:23.188 --> 00:46:42.108
Incoming livestream: you know, guarantees. I think especially for, sort of, customer-facing products and stuff like that, that is gonna be important, but, like, ultimately, I guess, because we're not at the point where we can fully trust that, we really want to lean on these more deterministic, architectural controls.


231
00:46:48.188 --> 00:46:49.048
Incoming livestream: Thank you.


